name: 3,4-dimethyl-cis-2-pentene
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: 3,4-dimethyl-cis-2-pentene has a melting point that can be predicted by considering its structural components. The basic unit for this compound can be considered cis-2-pentene, which has a melting point of -109.4°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The structural modifications we need to consider are the presence of two additional methyl groups. Methyl groups, when connected to a pentene ring, tend to increase the melting point due to the enhancement of the crystalline structure and the increase in molecular weight. In the case of 3,4-dimethyl-cis-2-pentene, we have two additional methyl groups linked in a linear fashion, which would notably augment the melting point. Each additional methyl group can be estimated to add approximately 10°C to the melting point due to increased molecular weight and rigidity.
